message: Hey! My friend (Natalie Rosen) and I are looking for two girls to share an apartment with us starting next fall! We have recently just signed with 412 lofts, which is right outside of Dinkytown, in a two bedroom, two bath apartment. You would be sharing a bedroom and it would be around $600 plus utilities, but the price is negotiable (they have a huge sale going on if you sign soon). If you are interested in getting to know more about us, then message us or comment! We would love to chat with you so that we can have an awesome year next year!

We crave significance.  We want our lives to matter.  We want to positively impact this world and bring change.  We all intellectually know that involves growing in our leadership and influence, but we can struggle to know what that looks like or how to go about doing that. Tonight from 7pm-8pm, Hope on Campus will meet in STSS (Bruininks Hall 330), where Pastor Cor will be sharing about what makes a leader, what doesn‚Äôt, leadership misconceptions, and how to grow in your leadership potential. Cor has been a pastor at Hope for many years and is the Director of the Leadership Development Institute for the past 7 years, which has helped raise up hundreds of leaders.  So, whether you sense God‚Äôs leading to be a lawyer, a teacher, a pastor, an accountant, engineer, nurse, doctor, or whatever options are before you, you won‚Äôt want to miss this opportunity to learn how to grow in your leadership potential! 

7pm-8pm. STSS 330. Hope on Campus. Oh, and Cor and I are leading a group to Applebee's afterwards! See you there!

message:
Figured the Foundations lecture is worthy of addressing since it replaced Shift. (Lengthy post, so hit the continue reading). Here's some reading and encouragement regarding the unjustified and incorrect claims made by Andy at the Round Table discussion. Don't be discouraged or frustrated about anything Norman (the humanist) said, from a philosophical standpoint he said very little that was actually sound. I'm sure there's more as well, so feel free to bring up in the comments anything else you had questions about or found encouraging. 

1) Abraham's blind faith. He never explained why it was negative, but here's a couple perspectives on what the story actually entails.

http://robbellcom.tumblr.com/post/66792774855/what-is-the-bible-part-6
The very point of it is that God did not end up forcing Abraham to sacrifice his son, which is contrary to the other gods at the time.

https://nathanstudanski.wordpress.com/2015/11/24/my-first-sermon/
Plugging my own writing here, the story is much more symbolic and foreshadowing of Jesus than he gave credit.

2) Slavery as negative- Apparently because America had blacks as slaves means the Bible had the same view. Slavery in the times of the Old Testament was not about race. Rather, it was about economic and social status, as was in the honor/shame culture. You could sell yourself for 6 years to pay for a debt, and you'd very likely be a slave and have slaves based on the social hierarchy where having followers helps your social status. 

Academic view of slavery in NT- it is much more symbolic of what our relationship with Jesus should be. 
http://www.ctsfw.edu/document.doc?id=214

3) Violence and his uncorrelated claims. I'm assuming his only references were to the OT, because he never attempted to justify his claims about modern-day Christians being violent. Similarly, his causation/correlation were uncited and do not prove anything. There's some examples here, so be careful about watching Nic Cage movies, since it correlates very well with death by drowning in a swimming pool. http://tylervigen.com/spurious-correlations

Are we viewing the violence as moral from today's standpoint, or 4000 years ago? Because if we viewed it as moral today, that'd be a problem. At the time, Christianity was very progressive in its views. 
http://robbellcom.tumblr.com/post/67678046281/what-is-the-bible-part-13

4) His view of the Bible. Of course if you're looking to come in with the lens of assuming Christianity to be bad, you're gonna shift things into your perspective. http://robbellcom.tumblr.com/post/68912921168/what-is-the-bible-part-17-assumptions-and-aa . He viewed everything based on the OT, with the exception of blasphemy of the Holy Spirit. Romans 8 is all about how Jesus fulfilled the requirements of the law. He also made it seem as if we have no evidence. Romans 1:20 "For since the creation of the world God's invisible qualities--his eternal power and divine nature--have been clearly seen, being understood from what has been made, so that people are without excuse." No evidence for resurrection. Okay, I'll run with that. So Jesus wasn't resurrected but authors of the Bible fabricated the whole story. To do so, they chose to use women as the primary witnesses, testimonies which would be immediately dismissed in court since only men were considered as trustworthy at the time. The women did not recognize who Jesus was. His followers did not even believe that he was resurrected. The gospel stories don't quite line up between the four. If you're trying to make up a story, why would you not work together to make it as sound and similar as possible with realistic witnesses? It would make no sense for the gospel writers to present the story in the way they did if they were making something up. 

What the Bible actually says.

1) Jesus gives unity to all things. This is far superior to the social advances made by humanism. http://robbellcom.tumblr.com/post/69088463619/what-is-the-bible-part-19-the-verse-that-blows

2) The Bible is not about being a good person or convincing yourself to have enough faith. Read the parables in Luke 15. What did the sheep do to earn his way back? He didn't do anything wrong by straying away, but certainly wasn't by his effort to save himself. Instead, the shepherd was willing to do something absurd to leave the other sheep behind and save it. What did the coin do? Again, this was linked to repentance. Once the sheep and coins talked in the parable of the two lost sons, how did the younger son repent? He came back only because of the famine and came back only hoping to improve his social status. Yet his father cut him off before he could sell himself out as a slave. What did the older son do to repent? He cut himself off from his brother and father by how he referred to them and by pouting outside of the house. Yet the father still welcomed him as a son. If Christianity was about what we do, none of that would be viewed as saving repentance. Yet the whole point is that all we need to do is be willing to be carried back to the flock. 

3) The message of the Bible is all about love (agape). One Corinthians 13:

If I speak in the tongues[a] of men or of angels, but do not have love, I am only a resounding gong or a clanging cymbal. 2 If I have the gift of prophecy and can fathom all mysteries and all knowledge, and if I have a faith that can move mountains, but do not have love, I am nothing. 3 If I give all I possess to the poor and give over my body to hardship that I may boast,[b] but do not have love, I gain nothing.

4 Love is patient, love is kind. It does not envy, it does not boast, it is not proud. 5 It does not dishonor others, it is not self-seeking, it is not easily angered, it keeps no record of wrongs. 6 Love does not delight in evil but rejoices with the truth. 7 It always protects, always trusts, always hopes, always perseveres.

8 Love never fails. But where there are prophecies, they will cease; where there are tongues, they will be stilled; where there is knowledge, it will pass away. 9 For we know in part and we prophesy in part, 10 but when completeness comes, what is in part disappears. 11 When I was a child, I talked like a child, I thought like a child, I reasoned like a child. When I became a man, I put the ways of childhood behind me. 12 For now we see only a reflection as in a mirror; then we shall see face to face. Now I know in part; then I shall know fully, even as I am fully known.

13 And now these three remain: faith, hope and love. But the greatest of these is love.

Got a bit long since I don't want to do homework, but hope that helps to anyone who was frustrated or even doubting from the event. Feel free to continue the conversation as well!

message:
Tonight's discussion really helped to reaffirm my belief in the Lord, which is why I love a debate; it'll either help you to find that you truly believe what you thought you believed in, or that your belief in something was really never there at all. Either way, there is always something to gain from a discussion.

Here are some C.S. Lewis quotes that were very thought provoking to me even before I became a Christian. Nothing else had ever made me question my beliefs so intensely before I saw these. They're quite the poweful rhetoric for anyone in a discussion or conversation about Christianity. They are points that I felt were missing from tonight's discussion, and I also believe they can be an effective tool for evangelism. I know it worked a bit of magic on extremely stubborn old me! Have a lovely night/day/afternoon/life & Godspeed :)

message: Hello! My friend (Emily Wangen) and I are looking for two girls to share an apartment with us starting next fall! We have recently just signed with 412 lofts, which is right outside of Dinkytown, in a two bedroom, two bath apartment. You would be sharing a bedroom and it would be around $600 plus utilities, but the price is negotiable (they have a huge sale going on if you sign). If you are interested in getting to know more about us, then go ahead and message us or comment! We would love to chat with you so that we can have an awesome year next year!

message:
Hello lovely people of UMN Cru.
Tomorrow is Friday (can I get an amen)
And that means Project Abide 
aka special time set aside for a Jesus date!!!
I'll be there bright eyed and bushy tailed at the Purple Onion around 8 am- come join me whenever.

For those who don't think they have the time (like me most often) - this quote from Francis Chan hits me:
"There is no substitute for being alone with God. If you don‚Äôt have time, you need to quit something to make room. Skip a meal. Cancel a meeting. End some regular commitment. There is literally nothing more important you could do today. 
Could anything be better? How can we not make time to be with the Maker of time?" 

And again the offer stands, if you want coffee, but only have $3 to your name and the coffee you want is $3.24, I'll buy! 
See you there.

Happy Tuesday everyone!
For those of you who for any reason couldn't make it to the spring break support raising events, you're still in luck! :D Send a completed support letter and a list of 10 addresses of potential supporters to me at ottox339@umn.edu by this Thursday the 18th, and you will receive a $50 scholarship to Big Break or New York.
Attached is a support raising guide, but if you have any more questions or need help writing your support letter, feel free to email/message me or any of the other Fireseeds!

Guys. It is only 10 days until the Big Break registration deadline! You can still register online at big-break.com, and you can even come to a support raising event tonight at the Cru House from 5-7. Come write your support letter, and when you have 10 copies ready to be sent, you get a $50 scholarship for Big Break (People going to NYC for break, this is for you, too)! message:
Hey all- are you or any ladies you know looking for housing? If so, the house I live in is looking for a lovely female roommate to join the crew! Rent is $437 a month including all utilities and there's an option to jump in on community groceries for $55 a month which can save a good chunk of $$ (versus going solo). We're also right in Dinkytown, so close to the U and all that good stuff.

You'd be living with six other amazing women who love God and across the street from some guys who are equally awesome. The house is pretty enormous, so although there's seven women there's enough space to spread out and be alone for you introverts out there-- as a fellow 'I' I can vouch for that!

If you're interested feel free to message me and we can talk details.
Thanks guys!

YOU Wont BELIEVE what today is....

Today is the last day to register for the NYC Spring Break/Vision Trip! Be part of the elite group of Cru students that choose NYC over PCB. The people that choose concrete over sand, culture over getting a tan, and the subway over a coach bus. Doing full time ministry for a week in a megacity like New York is a rare opportunity and something you'll never regret or forget! In the words of the great philosopher and theologian, Shia LaBeouf,

"JUST DO IT"

Feel free to message me if you have any questions or need the registration link.

(Disclaimer: Although I joke around and say NYC is better than PCB, I fully believe that either of these opportunities is the best way to spend your Spring Break. Also, I've never actually been to PCB so take anything I say about it with a grain of salt.)

Hope to see you tomorrow! Love y'all.

message:
The Timberwolves game is TOMMOROW!!!

What you need to know:
Timeline: 
5:00 most all of us are getting on the light rail (That is when it LEAVES) 
5:30 Check in at Mayo Clinic Square front desk for a talk from Timberwolves team President (there will be time for questions) 
6:15 go over to target center 
6:30 high-five players before game 
7:00 Game

If you don‚Äôt know where Mayo Clinic Square is (1st Ave and 6th St), it is attached to the target center, look it up on Google maps, Mapquest, Yahoo maps, Bing maps whatever you wish, but you cannot be late! 

If you need any help text me or call me at 612-965-3956

Also I believe that you can still purchase a ticket if you haven‚Äôt already!  There are 84 people signed up!

I understand this is a lot of information but I have no way of getting it to you all except for this post so tell your friends!

"Spiritual Autobiography (10%)
In 3-5 pages (grads 4-6) write your spiritual autobiography. If you get stuck, here are some questions to consider: Describe a memory of wonder or awe. Where have you found comfort when life gets hard? What has helped you be resilient in life? In your life experience what encouraged you to be spiritual and what didn't? What places, spaces, communities have been important to your spiritual life?"

Laugh with me, folks. Because for one of my classes, I have to type up my testimony. 

Freaking let's go.

message:
Hello everyone! The Timberwolves game is just 3 days away (1/23)! With that being so soon, I have some important info for everyone attending that was included in this week's email but here it is again in case you missed it:

You can still purchase tickets!! We want everyone to invite a roommate and/or a friend!! Let's make this a huge group! 
Cost: $23. Use this link to purchase your ticket: www.timberwolves.com/groupoffers
Use promo code: CRU
 
When and Where: Meet at the East Bank light rail station at 4:50pm. We will be getting on the train and leaving at 5pm sharp! 
Remember: the train leaves at 5:00 and people need to purchase tickets for the light rail before hand. Plan accordingly!
 
*IMPORTANT* Have your ticket ready to go before Saturday. 
To do this: 
1. Download the "Flash Seats" app
2. Login with the information you used to buy the ticket(s)
3. The ticket will be in the app to get into the game.
* If you do not want to do this, the debit/credit card you used to purchase the ticket(s) can be swiped when you get to the game to get in as well!

SAFETY PARTY
WHERE: BABY BLUE (1015 6TH STREET SE)
WHO: CRU AND ALL YOUR FRIENDS
WHEN: FRIDAY JANUARY 22ND @ 8 PM
WHAT: Safety Theme. If it's safe, bring it or where it. I'm wearing a lifeguard tube, seatbelt, and also inviting my mother. Mothers are the safest people in the world. Bring them.
WHY: Let's start the year with a great & fun party. But let's also be safe while having fun. Thus, Safety Party.

It may be cold, so talk to your Bible Study leaders about a ride!

message:
Hi guys, OneChurch is just around the corner! I don't know if you realize, but this event is kind of a big deal. There will be hundreds of believers from all different student organizations, churches, and ministries, and Nick Hall from Pulse straight up dropped a prior engagement in order to speak to us. God is stirring up the body to unite in worship, and we're aiming high believing that He'll come through.

Do you want to be apart of this? We still need more volunteers to help with things like serving coffee, greeting people, running a contact table for Cru, and spreading the word about the event. Sign up to help us make this vision a reality!

Also, please help by sharing the OneChurch event to get the word out. We want to see representatives from as many groups as possible, including other campuses in the area.

message: Hey friends!! As a leadership team we talked a lot about accountability, and I'd like to kick start that along with the new semester! For those of you who were involved in Cru last year, you may remember "Project Abide", or at least hearing something about it. It's a really great way for us as a community to hold one another accountable to spending time with God! I will be at the Purple Onion every Monday and Friday morning at 9:30, and would love to see as many of you there as possible! Let's start this semester off by intentionally prioritizing God and starting our mornings with Him, because He is worth it!!

message:
(Shameless summer missions plug) Still plenty of time to explore, pray about, or sign up for any of the various summer missions! http://www.cru.org/opportunities/mission-trips/summer.html . We've got 4 in our region for stateside- North Myrtle Beach, Jersey Shore, Badlands, and Milwaukee, as well as Paris, Australia, Tanzania, 4J, and a few other international ones. 

We had 17 Gophers in NMB last summer, I can honestly say it's the best summer I could have hoped for. You get ministry experience on the beach and at your workplace, but also 10 weeks of very tight community with 80 other college students who become your family for the rest of college and hopefully life after college. We had goals of 10 people to NMB and Paris last year, would be cool to hit them both this year since there's I think 3 or 4 to each already. Any age in school can go, we had people as old as 27 go as students, but especially for freshmen or sophomores if you're not ready for an internship in your field it is an incredible way to spend your summer.

If anyone's got any more questions about summer missions I'd love to answer them, and myself or one of the other Gophers who've gone before could meet up for lunch and discuss the summer with you. 

P.S.- SKOL VIKINGS

message:
Today is the last day to sign up for TCX.

This conference could very well be the highlight of your break!

I don't say that just to say it, but it was the highlight after my freshman fall semester when I was having a great time with God, and gained a ton of knowledge on missions and friends in CRU as a weird, awkward freshman.

After a really terrible sophomore fall semester, TCX really broke me and brought me back to God and spurred what was one of the greatest periods of growth with God in my life the following months.

TCX is dope, bomb diggity, and every other positive adjective in between.

http://gotcx.com/register/

Email Brad: brad.gustafson@cru.org if you need to contact him about financial needs. Finances are not an issue: we will make sure you go to TCX.

message:
YOU GUYS! Who is going to TCX?!?!? I can promise you it will be the most fun you'll ever have in your entire life and if it turns out to not be the most fun, Scott Khail or Roscoe Dash or Zach Carlstrom will take you to Skyzone. But since we know that's probably not going to happen because TCX really WILL be the most fun ever, you should just head on over to gotcx.com/register/ and register. 

But for real, TCX is a great place to meet more gophers, to grow in your relationship with God, to worship together with 1300+ other Christians, and to learn about God's heart for his people. We, as staff, are so excited for this time to come together over winter break as a movement, to pray together and to worship together. We'd love for you to be there. 

And for those of you who are thinking about it, but who feel like you don't know anyone who would be there, send me a facebook message. I would LOVE to help connect you to another student who will be there and who would love to hang out with you for the week : )

Serious post now. While we didn't hit our goal in order for the fireseeds to jump in the river, that doesn't matter. What matters most to us fireseeds, is that if you have any ounce of desire to go, follow that desire. Some of us have gone before and know how God can hit you so hard at this conference, and open your eyes to His plan for the next few months, the summer, and for years to come. I can attest to that. 

TCX is an incredible opportunity for growth and to finally dive into meeting numerous people from our campuses and the Upper Midwest. It's where I finally felt apart of the community Cru has to offer. 

Please pray about coming to this conference. We'll be in touch with some of you within the next week or so, but feel free to talk to anyone of us if you have any questions or concerns. 

If money is an issue, email Brad at brad.gustafson@cru.org. We don't want money to be a reason to not go, so we'll help out financially the best we can.

Sorry for all the posts today! I just am so excited for TCX and to grow alongside all of YOU!

message:
Everyone, sign up for TCX by tomorrow afternoon. If we get 70 people signed up, the fireseeds will be jumping in the Mississippi River. That is something you do not want to miss. 

However, the deadline to signup is Dec. 17th. Past that point, the price will increase, so pay now while it is just under $200! 

Love y'all and I really encourage that your pray about going if you're on the fence. It is an incredible experience where God will teach you a ton from dynamic speakers! 

See y'all there (:

message:
Hello everyone! Hope Community Church is hosting another "Hope on Campus"! Hope on Campus is a monthly gathering and training opportunity for Hopester UMNers. This is a great opportunity to listen to some teaching on specific topics on how to pull the gospel through all areas of life, to get to meet and know leaders of Hope, as well as have a space to meet other UMNstudents that attend Hope.  We invite you to come, partake, and just hang out!

This is also a VERY relevant topic in our city and country! Come learn more!

message:
I know the attacks in Paris hit especially close to home in our hearts because of our friends and loved ones who are currently there on stint or have been there on mission in the past, but I also think as Christians we should be mourning for the loss of ALL lives to acts of terrorism. Brutal attacks by ISIS have also occurred in Beirut and Baghdad recently, but have not received nearly as much attention by the media. This post is in no way trying to diminish the horror and grief we should feel about the Paris attacks -- just a call to expand our hearts and prayers to include the people hurting in other parts of the world too. God's heart breaks for all His children. #PrayforBeirut #PrayforBaghdad #PrayforParis

message:
Thank you deeply to all of you who came to pray with us today at the Cru house and also those of you praying from home. As heart shattering as it is to be glazed over with pain when we read the headlines, I kept feeling that this is a devastatingly beautiful time to come together. We stand firm in our hearts that trust not in anything but Jesus. We can come together to encourage one another; hand in hand, heart in heart, soul beside soul to pray for those affected by this tragedy. Our hope is not in this world and not in the folly of terror, but in a God who stands exalted and on High. I pray that we unite together in Christ to see healing, comfort, love, grace, and deep compassion for all peoples of all nations around the globe. Let our hope and joy come from a God who is sovereign over this world and is closer to those in suffering than we can imagine. Oh, how quick and swift He is to those who cry out to Him. Praise to our God... The great healer, The great comforter, and The great reconciler. 

God...bring forth your love, restoration, and glory.

#PrayfortheWorld

message:
Hey guys! The Cru house is open for renting next year!! Here's some info :)

Both apartments are up for rent starting September 1st.  Contact Pete Lehner for more information and showing. plehner@lindsaygroup.com #612-963-4844
 
Main Floor: 3 Bedroom (up to 4 tenants). Large living space. Full galley kitchen

Upper Floor: 4 bedroom (up to 5 tenants). New carpet / paint throughout fall 2011. Three bathrooms. Kitchen / living room. LOTS of storage

For Both: Front / rear door access, deadbolts on both. New well insulated windows throughout. Security lighting on all night around the entire building. Doors locked at all times. Off street parking available for rent. On site coin-op washer / dryer. Snow/lawn care/maintenance handled by property manager. Utilities included in rent. Internet: $25 per month per apartment. Internet jacks in each room as well as wireless wifi throughout apartment

message: Hi friends. :-) so I don't know a majority of you guys, but I know you love Jesus & I know that generally, people in Cru are exceptional human beings. So here's the deal, I have a friend, she's 21 & she has been battling juvenile myasthenia gravis since she was 16. This is an autoimmune deficiency that has gradually been causing her body to deteriorate. She has gone through an unbelievable amount of medical procedures in attempt to destroy this stubborn disease. To illustrate just how many procedures she has endured I attached a picture of her with her "courage beads", each bead represents a medical procedure. Hannah has been close to the end far too many times and had a very invasive surgery recently that failed, which is not a sign of hope for her. However, I believe whole-heartedly in the power of prayer & would appreciate it greatly if you all could throw in a prayer for Hannah to be healed and to be healthy again. Thanks friends, if you want to know more, there is a link on my profile. :-)

message:
Be bold in your classes and relationships about being a Christian! One of our missions as a Cru community is that everyone knows someone who truly follows Jesus Christ. 

Today before my class started, one of my classmates said she knew i was a Christian and asked me if i knew how she could go about getting baptized, as she'd never been (she has little faith background) and it has been on her heart since she'd been to a funeral that weekend. 

If you are BOLD in your faith, you are helping to complete our mission--if the Lord readies someone's heart for the gospel, if they don't know a Christ-follower, who will they go to to seek Truth? You can be that person! Be that person! Be open about your faith!

Love, one of the Cru seniors
Ps. Everyone is doing a great job. Keep growing!

message: Hi Cru family! So I don't know 94% of you but I wanted to ask for your support in a journey that God has recently put me on. This summer I will be in Thailand for 6 weeks working with an organization that rescues children (as young as 4) from sex trafficking and places them in safe houses where they can heal and grow in a safe, loving environment and learn about God. It's taking a huge step of faith because for starters...I'm an extremely emotional person so preparing my heart for such an experience is going to be tough, and there is a significant financial cost to the trip. I would so very much appreciate your prayers in regards to literally all aspects of this opportunity and if you feel called to also support me financially feel free to do so. You can learn more about my trip and/or donate at https://www.grouprev.com/tjs2016rachelabercrombie and there will be updates coming soon on my blog simplyrach.com So thankful for each one of you and what an amazing blessing it is to have the body of Christ!

message:
Calling all women in need of housing next year!
As many of you know there is "gospel houses" among the women of Cru and other ministries on campus. I live in the Lighthouse, known for its sheer number capacity of 18 women in one house. (And it's great) 
This year we have many Seniors graduating and leaving us (tears) So, the house is losing many of its members and we are being faced with a scary thought that the house may not make it to next year. 
I am one of the few that would like to see the Lighthouse continue to foster Christian community among women and I'm one of the few not graduating!

If you are looking for (very affordable) housing next year, contact me on Facebook or text me @ 3203396673 
We have lots of room!! 
(Ps if you don't want to live here but are in support, may you please pray for the house? Thank you!)

You can also contact me on facebook or text me at 763-234-5586!! WE WOULD LOVE TO HAVE YOU. 

This has also been posted in the cru women page

message: Hey everyone! Bridges, Cru's ministry for international students, is having another event on the 25th. This is a really easy way to connect with these students and to share the love of Christ with them. Also, if you're a bible study leader, invite your students to come with you! It's a great way to get them involved with ministering to the lost on campus. See you there!

Thanks for making it a great one (:

message: Is there ballaholics in the morning?!

International Justice Mission UMN has their second general meeting TOMORROW MORNING at 11am in Folwell Hall! 
We are a bunch of students passionate about seeking justice for victims of modern day slavery in the name of Christ. Slavery is the daily reality for over 27million people in the world today. The statistics are outrageous and we intend to change them.
Come to our meeting and check us out and see what you can do! Coffee and treats provided. Invite your friends and share this post. Like our page for more info on meetings and upcoming events!

message: Hello everyone, Nathan Studanski and I are seeing if anyone is interested in going to sky zone tonight. I believe it's ages 15+ after 8pm and it stays open until 11 pm. I believes rates for jumping times are $9, $13, and $17 dollars for half hour, an hour, and an hour and half respectively, plus a $2 dollar fee for sky socks. Quite honestly, you probably wouldn't need to jump any longer than an hour because it is a pretty strenuous activity, but super fun! I have car that fits 5 including myself, and so far I have 3 spots left. If that closes up unfortunately you will have to find your own way, but I really hope that you'll join me, it's going to be a lot of fun! If you interested just text me at 507-430-1236.

message:
Hello UMN:)  Hope you are all enjoying your summer adventures.

One of our goals as a region is to continue to improve our student resources on sexual wholeness. Can you imagine every students getting to have someone be real and open with them about the area of sexual purity during their first semester in school? What a difference it might make in their college years and beyond.

Specifically I've been part of working on a 6th Life Concept call "From Sexual Brokenness to Sexual Wholeness". It's hot off the presses and in need of some real life feedback. Thus my question to you...

Are any of you discipling someone this summer that you could go through this Life Concept with and give us feedback? It would take under 90 min and doesn't require any prep. I would say the audience could be HS or College. We are looking for it to be completed and have feedback given by Aug 1.

If you are willing, would you comment here or shoot me an email? londa.wagneratcru.org. Thanks everyone and would love your prayers for this to help students experience wholeness.

message:
Hey everyone! With summer on it's way and Cru wrapped up for the semester, one of the things I'm starting this summer (starting NEXT week) is a co-ed Bible study. It'll be more like a larger group meeting with worship, support, prayer, Bible study elements, and just overall a mid-week relief and place for you to come and join other believers who are in Minneapolis over the summer! Whether you're graduated or were just a freshman this past year, you are invited. You are VERY much welcome to join us. It's open to anyone who is or is not in Cru. We're just trying to create a restful, uplifting, intentional group to love God and encourage one another. Through this, hopefully we can grow closer to one another by the end of the summer and create deeper fellowship. 

If you are interested in being apart of this, I'll post more information in the coming days. Right now we are looking at possibly Wednesday or Thursday nights at 8:00pm. Location will be determined sooner than later. If you have any questions, feel free to message me on the ole BookFace or send me a text! More info to come!

For those of you sticking around the Cities this summer, 

Let's continue to be a community that encourages one another, points each other towards Christ, and pushes us to grow in our faith this summer!  I would love to find a night for weekly worship and prayer with you all outside under the stars.  Possibly Wednesday nights, after the volleyball matches that will be going down.  Let me know if you're interested.  We'll keep you posted...   

For those of you involved in the group last summer, "Summer Shenanigans" turned out to be a hit.  We thought we should bring it back. It's a new summer, time for new shenanigans.  In this updated version of "Summer Shenanigans 2.0," please feel free to post any pickup sporting games, impromptu worship nights, funtivities, and any events around the Cities that you think would be fun to get a group together to go to.  Please invite anyone that will be around this summer! 

Peace

message: I'd like to start a movement to change the icon for this group from the hand sign of the devil (very similar yet distinct from the "I Love You" sign, seen in the attached image) to anything else. The current icon is symbolic of Satan's devil horns, and can be frequently seen at Heavy Metal concerts while people proclaim "hail Satan". While there is certainly some contest over what the hand sign "really" means, some scholars claiming that the sign has been "misinterpreted" from its original meaning, the fact remains that the sign is sometimes interpreted as the sign of the devil, and certainly holds negative connotations that I feel we as warriors AGAINST Satan's evil forces should attempt to distance ourselves from.
